\begin_layout Standard
As the spools are moved around the track they rotate one revolution per
 trip around the track, twisting the cable once.
 This can be compensated for by taking the cable off the end results in
 one twist per loop removed from the spool.
 If the spools are wound such that the twist from cable coming off the spool
 cancels the twist from traversing the track there is no resulting twist
 in the cable.
 However, this requires the circumference of the spool matches the braid
 pitch.
 This would require a tightly wound spool for a tight cable braid, limiting
 the braid pitch by the minimum bending radius of the cable.
 This approach to eliminating cable twisting was unsuitable for attaining
 the high braid pitch desired for LEGEND.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To achieve a high braid pitch two improvements were made to the cable braider
 over the initial design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most importantly, the spools were oriented so cable was taken from the side
 instead of the end, so that there was no twisting induced by unwinding
 the cable from the spool (see figure 
